data.content:
## Migration Analysis

### Inventory of thread-termination APIs found

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Blocking call interruption |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop fallback |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Blocking call that needs waking |
| `while (true)` | `RunLoop()` | Cancellable work loop |

Both `Thread.Abort()` (throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`) and `Thread.Interrupt()` (obsolete `SYSLIB0046`) are broken in .NET 8.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle };

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns immediately when either the event is
            // signaled OR cancellation is requested — no Interrupt needed.
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);

            if (index == 1) // CancellationToken.WaitHandle fired
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items — the original code had a race
            // where multiple Enqueue calls could signal once, losing items.
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();       // signals token.WaitHandle, waking the loop
        _newEvent.Set();     // belt-and-suspenders: unblock if waiting
        _thread?.Join(5000); // wait for graceful exit
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

---

### Key changes explained

| What changed | Why |
|---|---|
| `CancellationTokenSource` replaces `Abort`/`Interrupt` | Cooperative cancellation — the only model that works in .NET 6+ |
| `WaitHandle.WaitAny({event, token.WaitHandle})` | Wakes on **either** a new item or cancellation, replacing `Interrupt` |
| `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop exits cleanly instead of being torn down mid-execution |
| Drain loop in `RunLoop` | **Bug fix:** original could lose items when multiple `Enqueue` calls raced between `WaitOne`/`Reset` |
| `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed |

---

### Pitfalls to watch for

1. **`Thread.Abort` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — it doesn't just "not work," it throws at runtime. You can't leave it as a fallback.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt` → `SYSLIB0046`** — obsolete in .NET 9, unreliable even in .NET 8. Only interrupts `WaitSleepJoin` state and throws a *different* exception (`ThreadInterruptedException`), not `OperationCanceledException`.

3. **Cancellation is cooperative, not instant** — if `Handle(item)` takes 30 seconds, cancellation won't take effect until it returns. If `Handle` is long-running, pass `_cts.Token` into it and check periodically.

4. **Signal-then-reset race** — the original `WaitOne()`/`Reset()` pattern can miss signals when multiple producers call `Enqueue`. The drain loop fixes this.

5. **Don't forget `Dispose`** — leaking `CancellationTokenSource` is a common migration bug. Always wrap in `using` or implement `IDisposable`.
